00:46:59.082 --> 00:46:59.850
President Obama: Cassandra?

00:46:59.850 --> 00:47:01.018
Female Speaker: Lisandra.

00:47:01.018 --> 00:47:01.752
President Obama: Lisandra.

00:47:01.752 --> 00:47:02.486
All right.

00:47:02.486 --> 00:47:04.021
Well, I'll tease
Sam about this one.

00:47:04.021 --> 00:47:05.122
(laughter)

00:47:05.122 --> 00:47:05.822
Female Speaker: Please do.

00:47:05.822 --> 00:47:06.623
(laughter)

00:47:06.623 --> 00:47:07.824
President Obama: Everybody
knows about you now.

00:47:07.824 --> 00:47:08.959
Go ahead.

00:47:08.959 --> 00:47:11.662
Female Speaker: My question
is around immigration.

00:47:11.662 --> 00:47:15.499
We've heard a lot about
your immigration policy for

00:47:15.499 --> 00:47:18.702
undocumented immigrants who are
currently living in the U.S.

00:47:18.702 --> 00:47:21.572
But what about hopeful
families that are seeking

00:47:21.572 --> 00:47:24.308
a legal pathway for
immigration into the U.S.

00:47:24.308 --> 00:47:27.411
but are finding seven- to
ten-year delays before they

00:47:27.411 --> 00:47:29.513
even can get to apply?

00:47:29.513 --> 00:47:34.518
I'd love to hear you talk some
more about your policy regarding

00:47:34.518 --> 00:47:37.888
shortening that timeline
and making it less onerous

00:47:37.888 --> 00:47:39.056
on the applicants.

00:47:39.056 --> 00:47:39.623
President Obama: Good.

00:47:39.623 --> 00:47:40.390
That's a great question.

00:47:40.390 --> 00:47:41.391
That's a great question.

00:47:41.391 --> 00:47:44.094
(applause)

00:47:44.094 --> 00:47:48.131
The United States
is a nation of immigrants.

00:47:48.131 --> 00:47:53.537
And this region has
contributed to the remarkable

00:47:53.537 --> 00:47:59.643
progress that the United
States has made over

00:47:59.643 --> 00:48:01.645
the last two centuries.

00:48:02.779 --> 00:48:06.817
And my goal during the
course of my presidency has

00:48:06.817 --> 00:48:09.820
been to make sure we
continue to be a nation

00:48:09.820 --> 00:48:12.055
of immigrants as well as a
nation of laws, and that

00:48:12.055 --> 00:48:14.825
we're attracting talent from
all around the world.

00:48:14.825 --> 00:48:17.828
Part of what makes us
special is you walk

00:48:17.828 --> 00:48:20.998
in Brooklyn and there are
folks from everywhere.

00:48:20.998 --> 00:48:23.133
But they're all striving,
they're all talented,

00:48:23.133 --> 00:48:26.837
they're all trying to make
their dreams come true.

00:48:26.837 --> 00:48:31.375
And that is what gives us
the energy and the strength

00:48:31.375 --> 00:48:33.644
to be able to accomplish
everything we've accomplished.

00:48:33.644 --> 00:48:41.485
So we need to fix
what is, right now,

00:48:41.485 --> 00:48:44.421
a broken immigration system.

00:48:44.421 --> 00:48:48.058
Part of it is dealing with those
who are undocumented but who

00:48:48.058 --> 00:48:50.260
have been living there a long
time, are part of the community,

00:48:50.260 --> 00:48:56.066
providing them with a pathway
in which they have to earn

00:48:56.066 --> 00:48:58.735
a legal status, but
recognizing that they're there

00:48:58.735 --> 00:49:02.639
and we're not going to be
separating out families.

00:49:02.639 --> 00:49:05.175
That's not who we are.

00:49:05.175 --> 00:49:07.344
That's not true
to our values.

00:49:07.344 --> 00:49:10.747
And ultimately, it's not
good for our economy.

00:49:10.747 --> 00:49:13.150
But you are absolutely right
that part of the reason that

00:49:13.150 --> 00:49:17.154
some people take the illegal
route is because we make the

00:49:17.154 --> 00:49:19.790
legal route so difficult.

00:49:19.790 --> 00:49:21.792
And so we're trying
to identify ways

00:49:21.792 --> 00:49:23.760
to streamline that process.

00:49:23.760 --> 00:49:25.796
Now, I have to be honest.

00:49:25.796 --> 00:49:28.498
A lot of people want
to come to America.

00:49:28.498 --> 00:49:32.436
So unless we just
had no borders,

00:49:32.436 --> 00:49:37.007
there's always
going to be a wait.

00:49:37.007 --> 00:49:39.209
There's always going to
be background checks.

00:49:39.209 --> 00:49:42.179
There's always going to
be some prioritization

00:49:42.179 --> 00:49:46.116
in terms of who's
admitted and who's not.

00:49:46.116 --> 00:49:49.853
But I do think that there
are practices we have -- for

00:49:49.853 --> 00:49:56.693
example, where someone has a
relation in the United States,

00:49:56.693 --> 00:49:59.863
is clearly qualified to
become at some point

00:49:59.863 --> 00:50:03.467
a legal resident and maybe
in the future a citizen,

00:50:03.467 --> 00:50:07.170
but in order to do it they have
to first leave the country,

00:50:07.170 --> 00:50:09.606
wait, and now they're
separated from their families.

00:50:09.606 --> 00:50:13.210
I mean, there have to be
ways in which we can make

00:50:13.210 --> 00:50:20.784
the system clearer
and less burdensome.

00:50:20.784 --> 00:50:24.087
Some of those changes we wanted
to make were in the legislation

00:50:24.087 --> 00:50:27.391
that was proposed and passed
the United States Senate.

00:50:30.694 --> 00:50:35.699
I think there is still the
opportunity to get that done

00:50:35.699 --> 00:50:39.002
before my presidency is
over, but it does require

00:50:39.002 --> 00:50:41.405
the Republican Party
I think to engage

00:50:41.405 --> 00:50:46.076
with me in a more
serious effort,

00:50:46.076 --> 00:50:48.078
and to put aside
the politics.

00:50:51.715 --> 00:50:53.216
Thank you very much
for the question.

00:50:53.216 --> 00:50:55.352
(applause)

00:50:55.352 --> 00:50:59.089
All right, this side
has been neglected right here.

00:51:03.193 --> 00:51:05.729
I'm going to go with this
guy with the beard, man,

00:51:05.729 --> 00:51:07.964
because he looks a
little bit like --

00:51:07.964 --> 00:51:11.101
(applause)

00:51:11.101 --> 00:51:13.937
-- he looks a little bit
like Marshawn Lynch.

00:51:13.937 --> 00:51:16.907
(laughter)

00:51:18.642 --> 00:51:20.043
Male Speaker:
Greetings, Mr. President.

00:51:20.043 --> 00:51:20.811
President Obama: How are you?

00:51:20.811 --> 00:51:21.945
Male Speaker: More life
and blessings on you

00:51:21.945 --> 00:51:22.779
and your family.

00:51:22.779 --> 00:51:23.613
President Obama:
What's your name?

00:51:23.613 --> 00:51:24.815
Male Speaker: My name
is Miguel Williams,

00:51:24.815 --> 00:51:26.883
but you can call --
I am Steppa.

00:51:26.883 --> 00:51:27.884
(laughter)

00:51:27.884 --> 00:51:28.518
President Obama: Steppa.

00:51:28.518 --> 00:51:30.120
Male Speaker: Yeah, man,
that is quite sufficient.

00:51:30.120 --> 00:51:31.955
Yeah, man.

00:51:31.955 --> 00:51:35.592
My question has to
do and surrounds U.S.

00:51:35.592 --> 00:51:41.331
policy as it regards
the legalization,

00:51:41.331 --> 00:51:44.201
the decriminalization
of marijuana.

00:51:44.201 --> 00:51:45.335
President Obama: How did I
anticipate this question?

00:51:45.335 --> 00:51:46.403
(laughter)

00:51:46.403 --> 00:51:48.505
Male Speaker: Yeah, man.

00:51:52.409 --> 00:51:53.877
President Obama: How did
I guess this question?

00:51:53.877 --> 00:51:55.045
Male Speaker: Yes.

00:51:55.045 --> 00:51:59.082
And, Mr. President, it really
comes under (inaudible).

00:51:59.082 --> 00:52:02.486
We face economic challenges
with the IMF, et cetera.

00:52:02.486 --> 00:52:06.323
And and we find realistically
that the hemp industry,

00:52:06.323 --> 00:52:10.494
the marijuana industry
provides a highly

00:52:10.494 --> 00:52:13.864
feasible alternative
to rise above poverty.

00:52:13.864 --> 00:52:20.003
So I am wanting to over stand
and to understand how U.S.

00:52:20.003 --> 00:52:23.039
is envisioning and how you
would you see Jamaica pushing

00:52:23.039 --> 00:52:26.142
forward on a decriminalization,
legalization emphasis

00:52:26.142 --> 00:52:28.144
on the hemp industry.

00:52:28.144 --> 00:52:30.981
(applause)

00:52:38.421 --> 00:52:39.389
President Obama: Okay.

00:52:39.389 --> 00:52:40.290
Well.

00:52:40.290 --> 00:52:41.758
(laughter)

00:52:41.758 --> 00:52:46.596
Let me -- I do want to
separate out what are serious

00:52:46.596 --> 00:52:49.132
issues in the United States
and then how that relates

00:52:49.132 --> 00:52:52.402
to our foreign policy and our
interactions with the region.

00:52:55.572 --> 00:53:01.211
There is the issue of
legalization of marijuana,

00:53:01.211 --> 00:53:04.814
and then there is the
issue of decriminalizing

00:53:04.814 --> 00:53:10.120
or dealing with the
incarceration and,

00:53:10.120 --> 00:53:12.155
in some cases, devastation
of communities

00:53:12.155 --> 00:53:16.826
as a consequence of
nonviolent drug offenses.

00:53:20.063 --> 00:53:24.968
I am a very strong believer
that the path that we have

00:53:24.968 --> 00:53:31.374
taken in the United States in
the so-called "War on Drugs"

00:53:31.374 --> 00:53:35.712
has been so heavy in
emphasizing incarceration

00:53:37.814 --> 00:53:40.884
that it has been
counterproductive.

00:53:40.884 --> 00:53:48.558
You have young people who
did not engage in violence

00:53:48.558 --> 00:53:52.796
who get very long penalties,
get placed in prison,

00:53:52.796 --> 00:53:58.335
and then are rendered
economically unemployable,

00:53:59.803 --> 00:54:04.407
are almost pushed into, then,
the underground economy,

00:54:04.407 --> 00:54:08.311
learn crime more
effectively in prison,

00:54:08.311 --> 00:54:11.748
families are devastated.

00:54:11.748 --> 00:54:14.317
So it's been very
unproductive.

00:54:14.317 --> 00:54:16.319
And what we're trying
to do is to reform our

00:54:16.319 --> 00:54:18.021
criminal justice system.

00:54:18.021 --> 00:54:20.624
And the good news is there has
actually been some interest

00:54:20.624 --> 00:54:24.794
on the part of unlikely allies
like the evangelical community

00:54:24.794 --> 00:54:29.332
or some otherwise very
conservative Republicans,

00:54:29.332 --> 00:54:31.401
because it's very expensive
to incarcerate people,

00:54:31.401 --> 00:54:35.805
and a recognition that this
may not be the best approach.

00:54:35.805 --> 00:54:38.041
So that's one issue.

00:54:38.041 --> 00:54:42.812
There's then the second issue
of legalizing marijuana,

00:54:42.812 --> 00:54:46.316
whether it's medical marijuana
or recreational use.

00:54:46.316 --> 00:54:49.452
There are two states in the
United States that have

00:54:49.452 --> 00:54:53.456
embarked on an experiment to
decriminalize or legalize

00:54:53.456 --> 00:54:58.128
marijuana -- Colorado
and Washington State.

00:54:58.128 --> 00:55:04.434
And we will see how that
experiment works its way

00:55:04.434 --> 00:55:07.203
through the process.

00:55:07.203 --> 00:55:09.205
Right now, that is
not federal policy,

00:55:09.205 --> 00:55:14.144
and I do not foresee
anytime soon Congress

00:55:14.144 --> 00:55:18.048
changing the law at
a national basis.

00:55:18.048 --> 00:55:22.585
But I do think that if there
are states that show that

00:55:22.585 --> 00:55:26.690
they are not suddenly a
magnet for additional crime,

00:55:26.690 --> 00:55:29.592
that they have a strong enough
public health infrastructure

00:55:29.592 --> 00:55:35.498
to push against the potential
of increased addiction,

00:55:35.498 --> 00:55:37.500
then it's conceivable
that that will spur

00:55:37.500 --> 00:55:39.703
on a national debate.

00:55:39.703 --> 00:55:42.672
But that is going
to be some time off.

00:55:42.672 --> 00:55:46.376
And then the third
issue is what will U.S.

00:55:46.376 --> 00:55:49.079
international policy be.

00:55:49.079 --> 00:55:51.948
And we had some discussion
with the CARICOM

00:55:51.948 --> 00:55:54.017
countries about this.

00:55:54.017 --> 00:55:57.087
I know on paper a lot of
folks think, you know what,

00:55:57.087 --> 00:56:03.493
if we just legalize
marijuana, then it'll reduce

00:56:03.493 --> 00:56:06.863
the money flowing into the
transnational drug trade,

00:56:06.863 --> 00:56:09.566
there are more revenues
and jobs created.

00:56:12.769 --> 00:56:17.607
I have to tell you that it's
not a silver bullet, because,

00:56:17.607 --> 00:56:24.447
first of all, if you are
legalizing marijuana,

00:56:24.447 --> 00:56:28.518
then how do you deal
with other drugs,

00:56:28.518 --> 00:56:31.121
and where do you
draw the line?

00:56:31.121 --> 00:56:38.461
Second of all, as is true in
the global economy generally,

00:56:38.461 --> 00:56:42.532
if you have a bunch of small
medium-sized marijuana

00:56:42.532 --> 00:56:45.401
businesses scattered
across the Caribbean

00:56:45.401 --> 00:56:48.438
and this is suddenly legal,
if you think that big

00:56:48.438 --> 00:56:50.440
multi-national
companies are not going

00:56:50.440 --> 00:56:56.446
to suddenly come in and
market and try to control

00:56:59.349 --> 00:57:03.586
and profit from the
trade -- that's I think

00:57:03.586 --> 00:57:07.056
a very real scenario.

00:57:07.056 --> 00:57:10.794
And so I think we have to
have a conversation about

00:57:10.794 --> 00:57:16.032
this, but our current
policy continues to be that

00:57:16.032 --> 00:57:19.536
in the United States, we
need to decrease demand.

00:57:19.536 --> 00:57:22.138
We need to focus on a
public health approach

00:57:22.138 --> 00:57:25.375
to decreasing demand.

00:57:25.375 --> 00:57:30.814
We have to stop the flow of guns
and cash into the Caribbean

00:57:30.814 --> 00:57:32.816
and Central America
and Latin America.

00:57:32.816 --> 00:57:34.818
(applause)

00:57:36.853 --> 00:57:38.922
And at the same time,
I think the Caribbean,

00:57:38.922 --> 00:57:44.527
Latin America have to -- Central
America -- have to cooperate

00:57:44.527 --> 00:57:50.266
with us to try to shrink the
power of the transnational drug

00:57:50.266 --> 00:57:55.672
organizations that are vicious
and hugely destructive.

00:58:00.076 --> 00:58:03.980
And if we combine a public
health perspective,

00:58:03.980 --> 00:58:08.685
a focus on not simply throwing
every low-level person with

00:58:08.685 --> 00:58:12.922
possession into prison by
trying to get them treatment,

00:58:12.922 --> 00:58:15.758
if we combine that with
economic development

00:58:15.758 --> 00:58:18.461
and alternative
opportunities for youth,

00:58:18.461 --> 00:58:20.897
then I think we can
strike the right balance.

00:58:23.633 --> 00:58:29.539
It may not comport with your --
completely with your vision

00:58:29.539 --> 00:58:33.643
for the future, but I think
that we could certainly have

00:58:33.643 --> 00:58:38.081
a smarter approach to it
than we currently do.

00:58:38.081 --> 00:58:40.850
Got time for one
more question.

00:58:40.850 --> 00:58:43.019
One more question.

00:58:43.019 --> 00:58:45.021
Let's see -- this
is always hard.

00:58:45.021 --> 00:58:48.791
It's always hard to be that
last -- it's a lady's turn,

00:58:48.791 --> 00:58:52.462
so all the guys just have
to put down their hands.

00:58:52.462 --> 00:58:54.464
It's too late for you.

00:58:56.933 --> 00:58:59.168
Let's see.

00:58:59.168 --> 00:59:01.170
You know what, I'm
just going to go with

00:59:01.170 --> 00:59:02.171
this young lady
right here.

00:59:02.171 --> 00:59:03.172
She's just right in front.

00:59:03.172 --> 00:59:05.375
Go ahead, yes, you.

00:59:05.375 --> 00:59:07.577
Hold on a second,
wait for the mic.

00:59:07.577 --> 00:59:10.713
(laughter)

00:59:11.848 --> 00:59:13.016
Female Speaker:
Afternoon, Mr. President.

00:59:13.016 --> 00:59:15.852
I'm Alana Williams (ph), I'm
from the South Side of Chicago.

00:59:15.852 --> 00:59:17.120
President Obama: Wait,
you're from Chicago?

00:59:17.120 --> 00:59:18.187
Female Speaker: Yes!

00:59:18.187 --> 00:59:19.322
President Obama: Well,
what are you doing here?

00:59:19.322 --> 00:59:21.090
This is supposed to be for
Caribbean young ladies.

00:59:21.090 --> 00:59:22.992
Female Speaker: Actually,
I attend Olivet Nazarene

00:59:22.992 --> 00:59:25.795
University and I'm studying
abroad, so I'm here.

00:59:25.795 --> 00:59:27.263
President Obama: I see, okay.

00:59:27.263 --> 00:59:28.197
Well, you're cheating
a little bit.

00:59:28.197 --> 00:59:29.699
I'll have to call on
somebody else after you.

00:59:29.699 --> 00:59:30.900
(laughter)

00:59:30.900 --> 00:59:32.101
But I'm going to go
ahead and let you ask

00:59:32.101 --> 00:59:33.937
a question real quick.

00:59:33.937 --> 00:59:35.471
Because I'll see
you in Chicago.

00:59:35.471 --> 00:59:36.572
(laughter)

00:59:36.572 --> 00:59:37.941
Female Speaker: Most definitely.

00:59:37.941 --> 00:59:41.277
My question is really
more so about home.

00:59:41.277 --> 00:59:46.182
I love my city, but the
violence is terrible,

00:59:46.182 --> 00:59:49.052
specifically amongst
young black men.

00:59:49.052 --> 00:59:51.454
And I know we're talking a
lot about police brutality,

00:59:51.454 --> 00:59:53.523
but I've lost a lot of
friends from people who

00:59:53.523 --> 00:59:54.624
look just like me.

00:59:54.624 --> 00:59:55.758
And that's the problem.

00:59:55.758 --> 00:59:57.760
And so I would like to
know what you believe

00:59:57.760 --> 00:59:59.762
is the true source of the
violence, and what

00:59:59.762 --> 01:00:02.832
is one solution to an
extreme problem.

01:00:02.832 --> 01:00:03.499
Thank you.

01:00:03.499 --> 01:00:05.068
President Obama: Well, look,
I know you asked it about

01:00:05.068 --> 01:00:07.603
Chicago but I know there
are neighborhoods right

01:00:07.603 --> 01:00:10.373
here in Jamaica that have
the same problems,

01:00:10.373 --> 01:00:14.310
and in every place all
across the Caribbean;

01:00:14.310 --> 01:00:16.312
certainly in
Central America.

01:00:19.649 --> 01:00:23.686
I don't think there is
just one single factor.

01:00:23.686 --> 01:00:26.255
Obviously, a contributor is
one that we just talked about,

01:00:26.255 --> 01:00:27.256
which is the drug trade.

01:00:27.256 --> 01:00:33.262
If you have an illicit
trade that generates huge

01:00:36.132 --> 01:00:41.037
amounts of money and is
not regulated above board,

01:00:41.037 --> 01:00:45.575
that is going to attract
ultimately people trying

01:00:45.575 --> 01:00:48.811
to carve out turf, trying
to control markets,

01:00:48.811 --> 01:00:50.413
and violence ensues.

01:00:50.413 --> 01:00:52.615
So that's point number one.

01:00:52.615 --> 01:00:56.986
Point number two is the easy
accessibility of weapons.

01:00:56.986 --> 01:01:02.158
And we were talking earlier
about different traditions;

01:01:02.158 --> 01:01:06.562
the United States has a
tradition of gun ownership

01:01:06.562 --> 01:01:10.533
that is deep; dates back
to the pioneer past.

01:01:10.533 --> 01:01:16.539
And I think it is a mistake
that we do not do a better job

01:01:20.176 --> 01:01:24.047
of putting in place common-sense
gun-safety regulations

01:01:24.047 --> 01:01:28.184
that would keep guns out
of the hands of criminals,

01:01:28.184 --> 01:01:31.154
but unfortunately a
majority of Congress does

01:01:31.154 --> 01:01:32.422
not agree with me.

01:01:32.422 --> 01:01:38.027
Even after six-year-olds
were gunned down viciously

01:01:38.027 --> 01:01:40.563
in their classroom, we
could not get action done.

01:01:40.563 --> 01:01:43.466
But what we are doing is
cooperating with the region

01:01:43.466 --> 01:01:46.602
as we are cooperating with
local jurisdictions

01:01:46.602 --> 01:01:49.906
to try to stem at least
the flow of guns using

01:01:49.906 --> 01:01:51.908
the administrative
tools that I have.

01:01:51.908 --> 01:01:53.943
So that's number two.

01:01:53.943 --> 01:01:56.979
Number three is providing
alternative paths

01:01:56.979 --> 01:01:58.981
for young people.

01:02:00.116 --> 01:02:04.454
If a young person is reading
by the age -- by the third

01:02:04.454 --> 01:02:10.393
grade and at grade level, if
they are enjoying school,

01:02:10.393 --> 01:02:13.629
if they see a path for
success, then they are less

01:02:13.629 --> 01:02:16.899
likely to get involved in
criminal activity and that

01:02:16.899 --> 01:02:19.535
will reduce gun violence,
and that will reduce

01:02:19.535 --> 01:02:22.538
crime, and that will
reduce death.

01:02:22.538 --> 01:02:23.773
(applause)

01:02:23.773 --> 01:02:25.374
Which means investing
in things like early childhood

01:02:25.374 --> 01:02:28.845
education and improving our
schools -- those things

01:02:28.845 --> 01:02:30.213
are absolutely vital.

01:02:30.213 --> 01:02:33.249
(applause)

01:02:34.717 --> 01:02:37.553
But there is a fourth
element to this,

01:02:37.553 --> 01:02:43.226
and that is our own
responsibility.

01:02:44.694 --> 01:02:46.195
And particularly, as I
speak to young people here

01:02:46.195 --> 01:02:49.098
today, we always talk about
what can we do about

01:02:49.098 --> 01:02:51.467
the violence as if it's like
just separate and apart.

01:02:51.467 --> 01:02:58.407
But we have control
in our communities

01:02:58.407 --> 01:03:01.477
of our immediate friends,
our immediate family.

01:03:01.477 --> 01:03:04.780
We influence our peers.

01:03:04.780 --> 01:03:11.020
And I do think that the power
that all of you have as young

01:03:11.020 --> 01:03:18.561
leaders to be able to not
make excuses for violence --

01:03:18.561 --> 01:03:20.563
because there are a whole
bunch of folks who have

01:03:20.563 --> 01:03:22.899
really tough backgrounds
and come from terrible

01:03:22.899 --> 01:03:26.035
circumstances, and
are really poor,

01:03:26.035 --> 01:03:30.006
but they don't go around
shooting somebody.

01:03:30.006 --> 01:03:35.578
They don't beat somebody over
the head because of sneakers

01:03:35.578 --> 01:03:40.349
or because they looked
at them the wrong way.

01:03:40.349 --> 01:03:45.788
And so there is an element of
us retaking our communities

01:03:45.788 --> 01:03:49.792
and being willing to speak
out against violence

01:03:49.792 --> 01:03:51.894
in our midst.

01:03:51.894 --> 01:03:56.098
That doesn't ignore
all the social factors.

01:03:56.098 --> 01:04:01.804
But Dr. King used to say it's
not an either/or situation,

01:04:01.804 --> 01:04:03.439
it's a both/and situation.

01:04:03.439 --> 01:04:05.875
Government has to act.

01:04:05.875 --> 01:04:08.978
We have to have
effective policing,

01:04:08.978 --> 01:04:13.749
which means policing that is
actually protecting as opposed

01:04:13.749 --> 01:04:15.751
to some of the things that
we've been seeing of late

01:04:15.751 --> 01:04:19.322
in the United States,
and I'm sure is true

01:04:19.322 --> 01:04:20.323
in other countries.

01:04:20.323 --> 01:04:27.363
And I say that saying that
police have an extraordinarily

01:04:27.363 --> 01:04:29.932
difficult job, and the
overwhelming majority

01:04:29.932 --> 01:04:32.068
do a great job under
severe circumstances.

01:04:32.068 --> 01:04:36.505
But there's got to be trust
built between the communities,

01:04:36.505 --> 01:04:39.075
and I had to put a task
force together that put

01:04:39.075 --> 01:04:41.077
together some excellent
reports in the wake

01:04:41.077 --> 01:04:45.014
of Ferguson around how
we can do that.

01:04:45.014 --> 01:04:47.016
But ultimately, what
happens in the home,

01:04:47.016 --> 01:04:49.885
what happens in the school
-- some of you are parents

01:04:49.885 --> 01:04:52.388
already; some of you will be
parents -- what we teach

01:04:52.388 --> 01:04:56.292
our children in terms of
values, valuing themselves,

01:04:56.292 --> 01:05:00.529
valuing others, that's
important, too.

01:05:00.529 --> 01:05:02.365
(applause)

01:05:02.365 --> 01:05:05.167
So there's
no single solution.

01:05:05.167 --> 01:05:07.003
But all of us have
to do better.

01:05:07.003 --> 01:05:11.674
Because the tragedy of what
we see in the United States

01:05:11.674 --> 01:05:15.511
but also in cities and towns
all across the Caribbean

01:05:15.511 --> 01:05:20.149
and Central America,
is terrible.

01:05:20.149 --> 01:05:22.885
And there's no
excuse for it.

01:05:22.885 --> 01:05:23.819
All right.

01:05:23.819 --> 01:05:27.556
Because I called
accidentally on a Chicagoan,

01:05:27.556 --> 01:05:32.428
I've got to call
on one more person.

01:05:32.428 --> 01:05:36.799
Look, this young lady stood
up, so she showed --

01:05:36.799 --> 01:05:41.737
that wasn't fair, but I
called on her, go ahead.

01:05:41.737 --> 01:05:44.206
You're not from
Chicago are you?

01:05:44.206 --> 01:05:44.874
Female Speaker: No.

01:05:44.874 --> 01:05:45.908
President Obama:
You promise?

01:05:45.908 --> 01:05:46.609
Okay.

01:05:46.609 --> 01:05:48.511
All right, get the
mic -- oh, I'm sorry.

01:05:48.511 --> 01:05:51.013
You know what, I confess,
even though I was going

01:05:51.013 --> 01:05:53.015
to call on you, she
thought she was going

01:05:53.015 --> 01:05:53.983
to be called on.

01:05:53.983 --> 01:05:55.985
I'm going to call
on both of you now,

01:05:55.985 --> 01:05:57.987
but each of you get a
really short question.

01:05:57.987 --> 01:05:59.689
Really short, quick.

01:05:59.689 --> 01:06:01.424
Female Speaker: Well,
I'm the team leader for

01:06:01.424 --> 01:06:03.292
the Global Entrepreneurship
Monitor and I want

01:06:03.292 --> 01:06:04.894
to thank you for the
initiatives that you're

01:06:04.894 --> 01:06:06.228
planning to do here.

01:06:06.228 --> 01:06:08.597
And I wanted to invite you to
our annual general meeting

01:06:08.597 --> 01:06:12.535
that's going to be held
in Babson in the States,

01:06:12.535 --> 01:06:14.503
so we want you to come
because you are part

01:06:14.503 --> 01:06:15.671
of a global team.

01:06:15.671 --> 01:06:19.008
So I'm representing Jamaica
as the youngest female team

01:06:19.008 --> 01:06:23.546
leader, and I'm inviting you
to come so we can talk

01:06:23.546 --> 01:06:27.083
about Startup America
and we can collaborate

01:06:27.083 --> 01:06:28.317
on different projects.

01:06:28.317 --> 01:06:31.120
So I'm inviting you
to come to that event.

01:06:31.120 --> 01:06:32.188
President Obama:
Okay, that was good.

01:06:32.188 --> 01:06:35.324
And I can say I'll
await your invitation.

01:06:35.324 --> 01:06:39.995
And what I will say very
quickly is entrepreneurship,

01:06:39.995 --> 01:06:42.765
small- and medium-sized
businesses,

01:06:42.765 --> 01:06:46.202
that is a priority and that
means that we've got to create

01:06:46.202 --> 01:06:53.909
channels for access to
capital, technical training.

01:06:53.909 --> 01:06:56.245
These are areas where a
lot of our development

01:06:56.245 --> 01:06:57.480
aid is shifting.

01:06:57.480 --> 01:07:02.118
Instead of just giving
somebody a fish,

01:07:02.118 --> 01:07:03.986
we want to teach
them how to fish.

01:07:03.986 --> 01:07:05.755
(applause)

01:07:06.288 --> 01:07:10.092
And what you're seeing
-- what you see among

01:07:10.092 --> 01:07:11.694
young people all
around the world is,

01:07:11.694 --> 01:07:18.534
is that instead of just finding
a job in a big organization,

01:07:18.534 --> 01:07:20.903
they may want to create
something of their own,

01:07:20.903 --> 01:07:22.071
a new vision.

01:07:22.071 --> 01:07:25.274
And that kind of creativity
has to be tapped.

01:07:25.274 --> 01:07:28.711
So we're shifting a lot of the
work that we do around issues

01:07:28.711 --> 01:07:30.713
of entrepreneurship, so I'll
be interested in seeing

01:07:30.713 --> 01:07:31.714
what you have to say.

01:07:31.714 --> 01:07:32.715
All right.

01:07:32.715 --> 01:07:34.717
This young lady
right here, go ahead.

01:07:34.717 --> 01:07:36.719
Female Speaker:
Hello, everyone.

01:07:36.719 --> 01:07:37.720
Hi, Mr. President.

01:07:37.720 --> 01:07:39.722
My name is Davianne Tucker,
and I'm the Guild

01:07:39.722 --> 01:07:41.724
president-elect for the
University of the West Indies.

01:07:41.724 --> 01:07:42.725
(applause)

01:07:42.725 --> 01:07:43.993
Thank you.

01:07:43.993 --> 01:07:46.128
So my question is, the
Jamaican government has

01:07:46.128 --> 01:07:48.230
been holding firmly
to the stipulations

01:07:48.230 --> 01:07:49.765
of the IMF agreement.

01:07:49.765 --> 01:07:51.767
There are many who would
like to know if the debt

01:07:51.767 --> 01:07:55.137
write-offs for Jamaica are
being considered as a means

01:07:55.137 --> 01:07:57.873
of improving the
livelihood of our people.

01:07:57.873 --> 01:08:00.109
So is that being considered?

01:08:00.109 --> 01:08:02.945
President Obama: Well, this
came up in my bilateral

01:08:02.945 --> 01:08:04.947
with your Prime Minister.

01:08:06.515 --> 01:08:12.521
And, look, historically, I
think there has been times

01:08:15.958 --> 01:08:18.994
where the IMF or the
international multilateral

01:08:18.994 --> 01:08:26.268
organizations worked
with governments in ways

01:08:26.268 --> 01:08:28.270
that weren't always
productive, got them deep

01:08:28.270 --> 01:08:31.273
into debt, and then
suddenly you've got a lot

01:08:31.273 --> 01:08:33.442
more flowing out
than was going in.

01:08:33.442 --> 01:08:35.578
And in some cases there were
governments around the world

01:08:35.578 --> 01:08:41.183
that were corrupt, lent money,
money goes into a Swiss bank

01:08:41.183 --> 01:08:46.622
account, suddenly the people
are paying off for decades.

01:08:46.622 --> 01:08:49.592
In Jamaica, some of it just
had to do with tough

01:08:49.592 --> 01:08:55.931
circumstances, not always
the best fiscal management.

01:08:55.931 --> 01:09:02.037
I think that the current
government has been wise

01:09:02.037 --> 01:09:06.242
to work hard to abide by
the IMF provisions.

01:09:06.242 --> 01:09:07.843
That's not been easy.

01:09:07.843 --> 01:09:10.679
And I think that has been
the right thing to do.

01:09:10.679 --> 01:09:13.582
But what I also agreed with,
when I spoke to the Prime

01:09:13.582 --> 01:09:16.218
Minister, is the need
to try to address

01:09:16.218 --> 01:09:23.726
in a more systematic fashion
how we can spur growth

01:09:23.726 --> 01:09:31.033
and not just put the
squeeze on folks.

01:09:31.033 --> 01:09:34.703
Because what it turns
out is, is that if a --

01:09:34.703 --> 01:09:37.439
the best way for a country
to reduce its debt

01:09:37.439 --> 01:09:40.943
is to grow really fast, and
to generate more income.

01:09:40.943 --> 01:09:42.845
(applause)

01:09:42.845 --> 01:09:46.916
Now, that does require
development plans

01:09:46.916 --> 01:09:51.453
and approaches that
are productive.

01:09:51.453 --> 01:09:54.423
And it is true that
sometimes that requires some

01:09:54.423 --> 01:09:55.824
short-term sacrifice.

01:09:55.824 --> 01:10:01.363
And I think the question
that the people of Jamaica,

01:10:01.363 --> 01:10:03.365
just like the people of
the United States

01:10:03.365 --> 01:10:05.367
and everywhere else,
should be asking is:

01:10:05.367 --> 01:10:07.369
If the government is
spending money right now,

01:10:07.369 --> 01:10:09.772
is it on something
that is going to help

01:10:09.772 --> 01:10:12.308
create long-term growth
and help people succeed?

01:10:12.308 --> 01:10:15.644
(applause)

01:10:15.644 --> 01:10:18.981
If the answer is no, you
shouldn't spend that money.

01:10:18.981 --> 01:10:21.383
Spending money just for
the sake of spending money

01:10:21.383 --> 01:10:24.453
is not -- that's not the
formula for success.

01:10:24.453 --> 01:10:26.455
But if the money is being
spent on what we talked

01:10:26.455 --> 01:10:28.457
about -- early childhood
education; if it's being

01:10:28.457 --> 01:10:31.327
spent on infrastructure;
if it's being spent

01:10:31.327 --> 01:10:34.296
on research; if it's
being spent on building

01:10:34.296 --> 01:10:38.734
skills for workers -- those
are good investments.

01:10:38.734 --> 01:10:41.103
And I do think that the
international financial

01:10:41.103 --> 01:10:45.074
institutions have to accommodate
the interests of countries who

01:10:45.074 --> 01:10:50.045
have a sound plan for growth so
that they cannot just stay

01:10:50.045 --> 01:10:57.786
in this static state but can,
over time, thrive and succeed.

01:10:57.786 --> 01:11:00.089
And the way that's going
to happen is because

01:11:00.089 --> 01:11:02.291
of outstanding young
leaders like you.

01:11:02.291 --> 01:11:03.993
I've had a great
conversation.

01:11:03.993 --> 01:11:04.994
Thank you, Jamaica.

01:11:04.994 --> 01:11:06.962
Thank you.

01:11:07.329 --> 01:11:09.231
Appreciate it,
young leaders.

01:11:09.231 --> 01:11:10.165
God bless you.

01:11:10.165 --> 01:11:11.033
(applause)

